When it came time to give our food orders, my partner ordered her dish...I ordered mine...etc, etc. Once everyone is done ordering I ask her if she could also bring me a water and she goes "Can you wait???" so she can finish writing whatever she is writing. Okay....

The food, although it was good, was nothing to write home about. The pancakes they claim are the best in the city, aren't. The amount of food on my plate was comical...I left there with my stomach still grumbling. Truly, you can get three times the amount of food for the same price at Denny's. And let me tell you...I'm small. I'm five feet tall and weigh like 95 pounds; it doesn't take much to fill me up LOL.

Would I return? Mm...maybe...in those cases where I'm kinda-sorta hungry and just want a "taste" of breakfast food.
If you don't go here and eat breakfast, then don't eat breakfast anywhere

2 stars only because the food came out quick and the pie was food.

Service is terrible, very slow, not friendly, and very sassy. To that I'm referring to the MANAGER and waitress. 

A couple tables were seated after us but were taken care of right away. Maybe because they're a table of 4 men I'm not sure but that's very unprofessional to leave another table unattended. 

Waitress first excuse for keeping us waiting was, "It's very busy." We aren't blind and can see that it's very busy but at least let your guest know you'll be right with them. Customers are able to see if you're busy or just messing around. 

While taking our order the waitress is leaning against the booth we're sitting in as if she's "tired." She really needs to be retrained from this company on how to serve guests, manage tables, serve guests in the order they're sat, and mostly not to lean on things while taking orders. 

The food came out fast. The clam chowder was ok. My family had the soup and sandwich combo which were ok as well. 'Nothing great, we'll just eat at sonics later,' is what we they said. I ate the coconut custard pie. It was ok. 

Overall this was a very poor first experience. I doubt I'll be coming back on my next trip to Las Vegas. 

I don't recommend this place to anyone and will be telling my friends to not come here as well.

I stayed in downtown Las Vegas and was absolutely CRAVING pancakes ! Never heard of this place so of course (thanks to Yelp) I was able to find the best pancake spot in old town! The location is within the Golden Gate Casino.It's kinda hidden so be sure
to have your eyes peeled.

My first impression of the restaurant was that it was very old fashion. Not in a tacky sense of course but in a sense where you feel there is some major history behind the restaurant. Everyone was dressed in a costume like outfit and we were seated pretty quickly.

The service for the most part was decent. However, not the quickest. Took us about 10-11 minuets to be served . The menu was filled with delightful treats and meal options BUT the price was pretty hefty. All of the items looked delicious but everything was so pricy. In my opinion that is the only reason why I rated this restaurant a 4 star. Although it was abit pricy I always remember that it is AlWAYS quality over quantity, so I gave them a run for their money and boy was I satisfied!! The food was delightful and the pancakes were to die for!

Hands down one of the best pancakes I have ever had. They give you the pancakes with fresh syrup and butter. Not just any butter but melted butter which is what really caught my attention as well as heightened my taste buds;)! I certainly recommend getting a tasty pastry or muffin on your way out.   Overall great experience !

I should clarify that my previous review was for the location downtown which has since closed. The current location in the Suncoast Casino doesn't even compare to the original. The food is NOT great and is VERY over-priced.

This place is an absolutely adorable 50's style diner. The staff is super friendly and fast. They give you large portions, and they're made fresh. They even freshly squeeze the orange juice from oranges in a bin. It's great! Also, the cinnamon roll is HUMONGOUS. I ordered it (expecting a normal sized cinnamon roll) and was given a huge cinnamon roll tower. It was warm, soft, flakey, and covered in just the right amount of icing. The prices are fair, and you get what you payed for, which is great food and service!
This place is a must when visiting Fremont St. It's all about the pancakes! They were so good! We also shared an omelette and cinnamon roll which was also amazing!

My 100th review deserves to be a 5 star one! Congrats DuPars! I've been hearing about this place for a while now. Old cafe style in a run down casino?! I'm there! Not to mention the claim of the "worlds best pancakes" was a bit intriguing. My daughter, boyfriend and myself were heading downtown not sure exactly of our destination and I remembered this place. If you valet park at the golden gate, it's a simple walk thru the small casino. Otherwise park anywhere allowed downtown and find your way. The waitresses and decor somewhat reminded me of a Waffle House. So right of the bat I was happy. The breakfast and lunch menu had TONS of comfort food classics. Never in my life did I think I'd order a meatloaf sandwich, but I did and was so happy about it. The kid had French toast with blueberries and the boyfriend went with a chicken pot pie. And then of course as a table we ordered a nice stack of pancakes. The super sweet waitress actually stopped and asked if we were serious when ordering all this food. (Did I mention I also had a $3 shrimp cocktail?) Well be proud miss waitress cuz we killed it ALL. The pot pie needed a little salt n pepper, but THAT'S IT! That's my only complaint. Great food. Genuine service. Exactly how I would expect an old school, cafe, Waffle House, waitress in cute outfits- type of dive should be! Well done.

AMAZING pancakes. They are butter basted and amazing. 

We also had a shrimp cocktail ($2.99) each, and the house made horseradish cocktail sauce had a great kick. 

We wanted to return, especially since this place is open 24 hours, but didn't get a chance to. However, this is going on my must-visit list.
Wait staff is 2nd to none!! I haven't had such good service in a long time. Food is top notch as well. Prices are reasonable quality is great. Definitely a keeper.

I really enjoyed the food here and was tickled by the $3.99 shrimp cocktail appetizer, which comes with a great marinara sauce. 

I got the Vegas stack--3 buttermilk pancakes with melted butter and maple syrup on the side. This was a standout dish. The pancakes were thick, fluffy and the butter didn't hurt either. I'm really glad I got the pancakes because they're famous for them.

Dining companions got the salmon and the New York steak sandwich. Sandwich was great but a little on the tough side.

The cinnamon rolls in the display case look like they're worth taking home, as do the pies.

If you love shrimp cocktails I highly recommend this place. They do have the best tails in town! The food is excellent! Breakfast, lunch, dinner, and home made pies. Everything  is amazing! My favorite is the cheddar tri tip sandwich. Its out of this world! My fiance and I visit Las Vegas often and we always eat here. Its located inside The Golden Gate Hotel which is also a nice place to stay.

I was really looking forward to trying Du-Pars.  Best pancakes in America?  I am so there.  Well the pancakes were very good, but I like anything drenched in butter.   I'm not sure they are the best in America but they might be pretty damn close.  

My husband and I split a short stack of pancakes and each got an omelet.  I was disappointed in my omelet, it was more scrambled eggs folded in half.  I like a fluffy omelet with all the filling inside, not a scramble.  Both of our omelets were overcooked.  The hashbrowns were good, but then again drenched in butter which is fine by me.  I got OJ it was expensive but it was fresh squeezed so what do I expect?  The best thing was the homemade jam they brought for with the toast.  It was sooo good.  

Similar to other reviewers we had a hard time finding the restaurant in the casino, had to wait for quite awhile to be seating when they weren't busy with no acknowledgement and sat in the back "no mans land" when there were plenty of spots up front.  Our waitress didn't check on us or see how we were doing.  Needless to say service was lacking.  

I wanted to try their desserts but was to full to attempt it.  Next time I find myself drunk and hungry downtown the pie is going down.

The pancakes were so huge, we split a large stack among 3 of us.  They were pretty good but not the best I've ever had.  Maybe I'm weird, because I know everyone loves the pancakes here.

The shrimp cocktail was pretty good, too, and a great value among 3 of us for a starter.

So...I here this place closed for a few days due to a couple of health code violations. OOPS. I still like it, check out my review from when I visited back in 2011...


 Du-par's is located at the Golden Gate Casino in historic downtown Freemont Street in Las Vegas. It is tucked away in a corner off from the casino floor, and if you can find it then its worth the search. I don't often recommend eating at a downtown casino however go ahead and give this a try. Du-par's has been operating in military like fashion since the stone age. The staff has been around the same amount of time, and we were well taken care of.   When we first walked in to the large retro style dining area at 5:00pm we were one of only a hand full of customers. One elderly man was just leaving and as he passed by and smiled he gave us an ominous warning "Stay away from the beef stew".  I'm not entirely sure if he was serious but we took his word for it and looked beyond that particular item. Simone ordered herself a pretty basic Roasted Turkey Sandwich on Wheat Bread. The Turkey was a bit dry but was nicely seasoned and thick hand sliced. The bread was good and the Lettuce and Tomato were Fresh. The french fries that came along side it were crispy and very good. Simone also ordered a side of Ranch for her sandwich.  I ordered the classic diner entree. Chicken Fried Steak. A ten ounce sirloin was pounded thin, thickly coated with seasoned flour and then fried to crunchy perfection. It was melt in your mouth tender and not greasy like I expected. It was served with rich and creamy Mashed Potatoes and very buttery delicious roasted vegetables. The potatoes and steak were both drowned in a thick stick to your arteries white peppery cream gravy. It even came with a fresh baked dinner roll for mopping up any leftovers.  This was a huge meal and altogether completely satisfying. In typical diner fashion the dessert menu was loaded with pies and pastries just begging to be eaten. At Du-pars , they further entice you by displaying all pies directly above the bar stool counter. We decided to try a slice of the sweet Pecan Pie of course topped with Vanilla Ice Cream. The crust was perfectly flaky and buttery and we finished every last bite. So don't be scared off by its location ( or its beef stew) stop in and give Du-par's a chance.

So excited to finally check this place out and was bummed.  I guess breakfast is the ticket here, but we did dinner and won't do that again.  I got the meatloaf special and it was not.  Looked alright, but just lacked flavor.  My dining buddy ordered the tri tip sandwich and it also lacked flavor and was nothing special.  The shrimp cocktails were great, but that has always been a Golden Gate classic.  Service was fine, but no reason to go back.

We took a side trip up to Freemont Street just to check out "Old Vegas". We arrived a little before noon and my wife was hungry. After looking for someplace to eat that was open and not a bar in a casino, we turned to my Yelp App to help us find a place.... And this is what it found. Ranked fairly high, we thought we'd try it. 

It has an old school diner kind of vibe to it. There is almost a feel of a 50's or 60's style diner. Even though they came highly recommended, we did not get pancakes. I'm not a pancake fan and we wanted more of a lunch style meal. My wife and I both ordered the meatloaf. What came out was okay, it wasn't great. The taste was fine, good homemade meatloaf with a mushroom gravy over mashed potatoes with spring vegetables. My problem was that the meatloaf was very dry. Thankfully it was swimming in gravy because other ways I don't know that I would have been able to eat it with out drinking something at the same time. The gravy itself wasn't all that amazing, standard mushroom gravy, it tasted like it was from a can. I do believe that the mashed potatoes where real as there were bits of skin in it, but I could be wrong. 

The service was good. Our waitress or another member of the staff would fill our drinks and check on us as we ate. Nothing all that spectacular. 

I could see why people would love this place, to me; it was just another diner to eat lunch.
The cinnamon roll was crazy good.  The omelette was huge and had tons of veggies.  The home-made jam was out of this world!  The service was awesome, never had to ask for more water.

Located in one of the most historic casinos in downtown Las Vegas The Golden Gate. Du Pars has with stood the test of time and itself has a storied history.  We had to order some of the signature dishes that have allowed this place to sustain itself for generations.  

Traditional pancakes were huge thick and fluffy, and served with a large dollop of butter and traditional maple syrup.  The pancakes were very well done and cooked perfectly. I recommend trying this dish.

The Patty Melt was next. Served on grilled rye bread with grilled onions and melted swiss. This dish was also executed well. Cooked to a perfect medium you can tell this kitchen has made 1000's of this dish.   The dill pickle on the side was also very delicious. 

The Veggie Burger was also tasty. Topped with cheddar LTO and Avocado was it's hard to mess this dish up.  Served with a large portion of french fries and pickle. You will not go hungry ordering this dish.

Overall food was good, but priced for tourists which means expensive.  Don't get me wrong the food quality is good but not a place you can venture to regularly.  Unless your Howard Hughes.

I'm currently in Las Vegas celebrating my birthday with my girlfriend and a few friends. When i booked our room on Fremont Street I knew I had to go to Du-Par's and try the word famous $2.99 Shrimp Cocktail. After a nice run playing Let It Ride at the Four Queens Casino, I headed over to Du-Par's to grab a snack before dinner. I sat down at the bar and ordered a water and a Shrimp Cocktail. It was served in a sundae cup, with house made cocktail sauce, crackers, and a lemon wedge. It's the best cheap cocktail i've had in Vegas so far! It's not the itty bitty shrimp with lettuce or celery and a packet of cocktail sauce. I actually ended up coming back 2 more times before we checked out. I had the Beef Tri-Tip Stew, the beef was tender and the vegetables were cooked perfect. I also had the beef and Barley soup, It was tasty, the broth was rich, and it had a nice tomato flavor.

Good Atmosphere, Fresh Food, Friendly Service, and Lots of History.

Came here to carbo load before a race.  I must say, they do carbs well!  

Pancakes were huge, fluffy, and perfectly crispy.  Melted butter to pour on top was nice.  

French toast was also very good.  

Bacon and eggs were as expected.  The hash browns were thick and nicely crisped.  

Basically an older diner that just does the basics well.  The blueberry muffins are large and interesting.  Nice sugar glaze and pretty big.  Very popular so they're always making them.  That means they're very fresh.  Don't forget the pies as well.  We tested out the chocolate cream for dessert.  

Just at the end of fremont street at the golden gate hotel.  We'll likely make this a stop next time we stay downtown.

Go for shrimp cocktail, not pancakes.  I know this place is supposed to have the best panckes in the US/world (I don't remember), but seriously 2 panckes for $7.35?  Pancakes were just okay, nothing to get excited about.  I felt dooped.  Now the shrimp cocktail was good.  Nice, tangy cocktail sauce.

It's true, their pancakes are the best! I seriously appreciated the melted butter! ;) I had an omelet which was perfectly prepared. I also tasted their cinnamon roll and that was great too. I want to bring my mom here since she is a breakfast fan. I haven't tried lunch or dinner here but I'm sure I will in the future.

Love this place! Shrimp cocktail is great value. A little more expensive than the .99 cocktails, but much larger shrimp and much better cocktail sauce. The pie is also really good. Great service from Joe!! deserves a raise! ha ha. would come back for good service.

This place has never disappointed. I come in here all the time for the breakfast. Their stack of pancakes is probably the best ever! So massive and very well priced! There's some contest where if you eat 15 you can get the stack for free, I would never manage but I offer you the challenge! I have also come here on other occasions for their shrimp cocktail. It's massive and can definitely fill you up even though I'm sure it's meant as an appetizer. 

The place also has loads of history which is really cool to discover when traveling to a new city. Their menus give a good description of Du-par's and it's legacy in Vegas. 

The service here is amazing and there's always a line out the door but you'll get seen to quickly enough. This is my regular joint while downtown.
Love this place.  Every trip to Vegas where we stay on Freemont we eat here...way too often.  Great stuff!  Go there!

Du-par's, located inside the Golden Gate on Fremont, actually set the bar for the best eggs benedict I have ever had. The eggs were cooked perfectly and trust me, i have had many a disappointing and over cooked egg. Every time it happens i reminisce about how beautifully poached my eggs were here. It will always hold a special place in my heart. The service also rocked and the pie slices i got to go definitely hit the spot a few (ok a bit more than a few) beers later. It's a great little diner atmosphere with egg-cellent breakfast and baked goods.

Stepping into Du-par's is stepping into a piece of LA dining history from 1938 (where it originally opened) as well as the history of the Golden Gate Casino of Las Vegas.  This historic hotel with address #1 Fremont Street, actually opened in 1906 where room/boarding was $1/night while the Du-par's franchise opened in 1955.  It may look like a just another small diner to you, but this one has great track record and authentic charm.  We decided to try it out for the first time on Sunday lunch.  There was a line to get in, and there were shelves displaying their baked donuts, cinnamon buns, huge blueberry muffins, and pies ranging from lemon meringue to coconut cream.  We were drooling on our way in.

The floor tiles are checkered black and white, the dining bar and ceilings made of dark wood, the stools and booth seats of red leather and the walls are dotted with old photos.  I am pleased to hear my toddler drowned out by the loud voices and plates clanging around.  The waitress in her vintage uniform takes our orders and come back with them in a period between good time and waiting too long.  No reason to complain considering the crowd.  Hubby was pleased with his eggs benedict (its pretty hard to mess this up) and I was quite happy with my meatloaf.  Yes, I missed meatloaf.  This one was packed with meat and was tasty, and the mushroom gravy was good, although I kinda missed eating it with catsup.  If you are a catsup meatloaf gal, ask for the gravy on the side.  The chocolate cream pie looked better than it tastes, I would probably go for another pie ala mode next time.  And of course, we couldn't miss out on the famous fluffy pancakes.  It was large and yummy, and yes, fluffy.  

I did have one complaint though, the pancake syrup although good was a little too... fluid for my taste (I prefer my syrup thicker), and since the pancake doesn't really have any crust, when it absorbs all the syrup it gets quite soggy.  So they definitely earn the fluffiest pancakes for sure, but the best in Vegas?  That is debatable.  The prices are not cheap for diner fare, however the servings are hefty so I believe you are getting a good bang for your buck.  Order a couple of plates and desserts to share with friends and try to go during an odd hour so you can dish more historical stories from the servers.  This is definitely a spot that should be on a Vegas eat list.  (P.S. The Golden Gate Casino introduced shrimp cocktail to the Vegas scene in 1959, so you might want to order that here as well :)

Great place to have shrimp cocktail! The pies are really fabulous. Service is great by the wait staff but my main complaint is with the hostess/cashier.  That little woman keeps people waiting unnecessarily and will walk away from people at the cash register to check for tables.  Other time we have seen open table and no one at the register and she goes to bus a table when there is a bus boy. 
Food is great.  The burgers are tasty. The French dip is wonderful with great au jus.  Huge salad and good soups.  Pancakes were great. Cinnamon rolls were heavenly. Food is good but do NOT skip the shrimp cocktail because it is a landmark.
Had breakfast 2 days in a row and defiantly well worth and our server Erica was great!! Food was awesome!!

I always go here when I'm downtown.  I mean who can resist $1.99 shrimp cocktails!!  Not I!!  The bread and pastry are freshly made and the meat is freshly sliced.  I always get the shrimp though, that's usually a steal for my late night drunken snack.  

The ambiance could be better, but for $1.99 I can't complain too much.  Seating is cafeteria style and everything is self served.  It's like being back in the high school lunch line, but the food is much better.

First time here, even though there is a location at home (Pasadena). Came here for a late lunch to what this place was all about. When entering, it almost look like old style diner. 

Items we ordered-
French dip
Country Chicken. 

Both were very delicious dishes. The french dip was tender and flavorful. As for the country chicken, it was battered well and the chicken was not dry at all! Gravy tasted great, not too heavy.

Definitely give it a try if you are in the DTLV area. Its located in the Golden Gate Casino.

We have been here a few times and I am upset that I had not starting here much earlier. We had a breakfast reception held here for the day after our wedding to host our dearest friends and family and they were all impressed with the food. Don't get me wrong, this place is not a fancy place by any means but it is a remarkably great place to get awesome food 24/7. I have only been for breakfast but their pancakes are the best I have had. I don't know what kind of magic they sprinkle on these suckers but they are awesome. I tried the shrimp cocktail and I was a little hesitant at first. It doesn't look like anything special but I had not one but two! Good value for the money. The menu is a little pricey at first glance but the food is definitely worth it. Great portions and good quality. Highly recommend to anyone local or out of town!

Alright guys, I give it 5 stars even though my omelette & hasbrowns were average.

THE PANCAKES.

If you go there and don't get the pancakes, you messed up.  They are the best I can remember having.  They are light, fluffy and a little crispy on the outside.  They're also huge.  I had a blueberry muffin that was also good, that I forgot about bc of the pancake awesome.  Service was good and the other food was good enough.
We stopped in late and grabbed the famous pie. It was pretty good - we shared a slice of apple a la mode and some coffee.

Had to wait in a short line for about 10 minutes when the host said there was availability at the counter. My group of 3 came for dessert only. They have a wide assortment of pies and a few other options such as a brownie sundae and bread pudding. I went with the strawberry pie which was really strawberry cream. Let me tell you the graham cracker crust was to die for! So crunchy and flavorful!

Total for 3 slices of pie a la mode for the group? $18.11

The place was busy, but the counter experience made it fun. Looks like breakfast is where it's at for this joint.

This place is a hidden gem when you are in Vegas. 

When you are in Vegas and ask a dealer, Pit Boss, Taxi driver where they go to eat go food they will tell you Du-Par's. 

Du-Pars are famous for their $1.99 Shrimp Cocktail which is packed with Shrimp and their Steel Coat Oatmeal with fresh fruit for Bfast, which is simply amazing. 

We stayed in Vegas over the weekend and had several meals from Bfast, Lunch to Dinner here. Du-Par's has Prime Rim, Hamburgers, Fresh Baked cakes, cookies, to you name it they have it. 

The day I ordered the steel cut oatmeal I also ordered a Fresh Cinnamon roll warmed for our table and after the first bite it did not last very long. I will say that I ordered hash browns burnt and they were a little too (Shinny aka Greasy for my stomach so I did not eat them). 

The staff is great, there is never a wait longer than 5-10 minutes to sit and if you are looking to get a quality meal that you will find on the strip inside a restaurant in a casino for 25 times the price this is the place you should be trying. 

I have been coming here for years and I will continue coming here for years. 

I dig the placemats on the table that have the history of Downtown Vegas and Du-Pars from 1908 to current day. 

This place is definitely worth a try.
The little hidden gem in Vegas great place to get great breakfast check it out

Awful awful awful! Disgusting, looking terrible  food. Slow lazy waitress. Plastic cups for souses , old disgusting utensils. guy from valet parking wearing dirty clothes just hanging around food facility , small talking to waitress. Dirty old tables and chairs. Dirty bad looking cooking table. Only one thing good looking there is fridge with pies. We paid 50$ for terrible omelets and pancakes.  No fruits, no toast, nothing. Hash-brown was tasteless.  If you want better breakfast in this area, just go to the golden nugget or plaza. Even Dennys is better!

I have been eating here for 20 years. This is not a 5 star fancy restaurant. Its not suppose to be. Its a dumpy old diner not renovated since the early 1900s and that's why I like it. 

Simple menu. Great staff.

Prices... this place used to be cheap. However the new owners known as Dupars took over last year and prices went thru the roof. You could.eat dinner here for $8 now expect to pay $28.
FINALLY!!!! I felt like a little kid in a candy store.... I love breakfast... and even better after a night and day of drinking and Vegas fun!!!

This was a researched breakfast spot for me and Kelly. Definitely wanted to start off on this spot to kick off a morning of Fremont Street morning fun. When we got here we were seated immediately. The front of house greeter was pleasant and engaged us on the way to the table. Our server was on us fast and took our coffee and juice order. We needed coffee bad. Coffee came and it was glorious... Bottom line it was great diner coffee. If you have had commercial barista-type coffee, you know the value of good old fashioned diner coffee. We ordered their famous shrimp cocktail as a starter... yeah I know.. breakfast shrimp? Yes, and it was great! The server said people do it all the time, so I was not labeled as a freak. We got the traditional Eggs Benedict. The hash browns were crisp perfection and the Bennies were built well. The Canadian bacon was thick, but we could have had a little more hollandaise sauce to take it up a notch. It wasn't a huge plate of food, but it was done right. My wife and I sheepishly ordered a short stack of what they are known for, pancakes. In less than two minutes they were being served. The server let us know he gave them a slight bath with melted butter. Oh, he knew us well. I can say this honestly and until I have better, these will go down as the BEST pancakes I have ever had. They were thick, fluffy and had a delicate, almost caramelized texture to them that was perfect for a texture junky like me. The server had some conversation with us and told us how much he loved working there. That means a lot when someone compliments where they work in these days. I highly recommend this to foodie hunters.

I think I made a few mediocre menu selections here. What were they? Glad you asked!

The chicken noodle soup: Dare I say I'm a chicken soup connoisseur? You're damn right I'm a chicken soup connoisseur! Does that mean I'm picky? Nope. I give the benefit of the doubt and I know that not all soups can live up to my expectations, but above all else chicken in soup should never be dry. How is it even possible when swimming in broth?

The French dip sandwich: A classic hangover meal for me and a pretty damn good gauge when it comes to diner food. Unfortunately this dip fell a bit short on a few levels. First of all, for around $12.00 I expected a little bit lager sandwich and it was easily consumed in 6-8 bites. How about some more dry meat? You got it! To round it all out they are stingy with the beef au jus, which mean you have to be stingy with the au jus. When it comes to French dips, I dip and I dip hard. Dainty dipping just didn't cut it. 

Expect this star rating to go up because I'm sure to be back with some better menu knowledge.

$2 shrimp cocktails please

My girlfriend took me here on a spontaneous weekend in Vegas.  I have had their food before but for take out.  Last time was my first experience dining in.  We came in on a Saturday around 3pm and there was a short line for a table.  Once seated, our friendly waitress came over to take our orders.  We went for two shrimp cocktails, shared a cheeseburger with fries, and their month special chocolate strawberry slice of pie.  The shrimp cocktails came out prompt.  They came out nicely presented in a sundae cup filled to the rim.  It was topped with lots of cocktail sauce and some crackers on the side.  We asked for horseradish on the side and they gave us a lot quickly.  The shrimps tasted like they were from frozen but come on... for $2 each, you can't really complain.  The cheeseburgers and fries were nothing special.  They were just exactly what it is.  Nothing more nothing less.  The chocolate strawberry pie though, was divine.  Their pies here really are the best.

The total was cheap.  The prices are reasonable.  I love all their pastries here.  There were a lot of people who would buy a bunch of their pastries or pies to go.  The service was also great.  Our waitress made sure we were taken care of and the food came out fast.  The inside is outdated with a totally diner feel.  Most of the customers are elderly.  There are two dining areas.  One closer to the front where the cashier is and one in the back.  There are plenty of tables and booths.  When we left, there was a long line that formed for people to be seated.  Overall, it's been a little hidden gem for us when we want some cheap shrimp cocktails.

Sometimes a place suffers from too high expectations.  This was that place for me. The pancakes had a great flavor but everything else was basically Dennys. The service was meh. Just didn't do it for me especially for the price. Just a casino coffee house.

I just, formally, met Rose Pinocchio, the GM of the LV Dupar's. WOW.
While I have seen her in action during previous breakfast excursions, I introduced myself today, at her request, due to a bad experience I had had during an evening service. I must say that I am truly impressed. She informed me that, not only had she taken immediate action to correct the problem, but that she also posted my scathing Yelp review for all to see.
Rose also introduced my group to the gentleman who will be heading up the new Dupar's in the San Diego Gaslamp District. If he is half the professional that Rose is, then his restaurant will be a smashing success.
Overall, I have always been loyal to the breakfast at the Golden Gate Dupar's. It simply has the BEST morning fare in LV. Now, however, I consider myself a loyal Dupar fan--at all hours, because of a true customer appreciation.

I was disappointed by my breakfast at Dupars. I ordered a simple two egg breakfast with hash browns and sourdough toast. The eggs were very bland, the hash browns were toasted to a crisp on the top and bottom, but mushy inside, and the toast had a ton of butter on it (which I should have remembered to request dry). Personally, I felt most items on the menu were just too expensive for diner-style breakfast. 

Our waitress was helpful and coffee refills were quick, but I wouldn't go back.

Small old school diner in the heart of DTLV. After a weekend at Life is Beautiful, I was looking forward to breakfast here. This was definitely the highlight of my weekend. 

While waiting in line for a table, I was able to drool over the pie case and all the lovely pastries being displayed. After being sat, we all ordered the famous shrimp cocktail (it only makes sense to pair it with breakfast) and of course the pancakes. I'm a definitely not a pancake lover. I don't like syrup, and when I do have pancakes (which is very rare) I need peanut butter to top it. Well, these pancakes were amazing and they live up to all the hype. The fluffiest, velvety stack I've ever had. They served a boysenberry syrup with it, made in house, and this really gave it the flavor I needed since I don't do syrup. Portions are pretty large, so my friend and I did split the pancakes and omelet. Unfortunately we didn't save room for pie. Always next time.
Great breakfast.  Husband picky pancake eater. He loved the pancakes, eggs, bacon, sourdough toast oh and the cinnamon roll.  2 thumbs up and will come back

With all the great food choices in the East Fremont district don't waste your time or food budget here. The service was friendly but took forever for medium quality diner food. The hash browns were not quite cooked through and the whole thing was really pricey for what it was. You can eat at a diner this bad in just about any town in America for half the price. My advice to the managers is to eat at some other restaurants around town and step up your game!

A little bit too old school. Could modernize their menu. Waited in long line though there was plenty of room at the counter. No menus. No silverware  Too expensive and no sides. Everything is extra. Weird.
What a great place for breakfast. The pancakes are to die for. No problem getting egg whites and they were fluffy and delicious. Great service as well. Will definitely return.

Great Breakfast Food served up fast and friendly Huge Pan Cakes Good Coffee and the price isn't too bad I also seen them Fresh Squeezing Orange Juice I wish I would of known earlier but next time if your in a hurry they have a bakery case full of muffins and doughnuts and other pastries that looked real good

Never even got served my short stack after 45 minutes.  First time I ever walked out of a restaurant.  They could have cared less.  Unless you don't mind being treated like dirt don't go their go to this place.

Pancakes...pancakes...pancakes...that is all!  I am not typically a big pancake fan but after reading the reviews I decided to give them a shot.   Believe the hype because they are the best pancakes I have ever eaten.  They are crisp on the outside and fluffy on the inside.  In fact, if you can eat 10 of them (which would be ridiculous) you get them for free.  

My husband had the salad and the shrimp cocktail.  The shrimp are small but the cocktail sauce is homemade.  It was pretty darn good but they have increased the price to $3.99.   I remember as a kid getting one for $.50...darn inflation!  Seriously do try the shrimp cocktail. 

The service this time was actually pretty quick but we were there at an off time.  Other times the service has been very slow.   Service is definitely hit or miss.

Also, check to see if you have any comps there if you are a gambler.  We had $10 in free meals so it was a great deal.

I cant really say their famous pancake is good or not... Ultra greasy and buttery - kinda chewy,,, I guess it is an old style pancake that your dead grandpa loved,, or something like that. I still like it,, but I dont know I should give even,,,4 stars.

Pies are the same. They are ultra sweet - Not special at all. I prefer Marie Callenders. 

Everything - atmosphere, taste, service is oldschool - and it might make elders feel comfortable. Its all about nostalgia. I love it. I keep going back. But I just cant say the food is good,,, to be honest. 

Well, who expects great food at diner anyway? I would kill myself if they start to serve Spanish tapas and Spider rolls...

Recommended by a friend who is a Vegas local for their pancakes. 

So I had a bite of the pancakes and the French toast and it was full of buttery deliciousness.  I think that's what makes it so good. If I weren't so concerned with gaining tons of weight, I would have gone for the pancakes. 

But I opted for the Avocado Turkey Eggs Benedict.  It was YUM-Tastic!  I forgot to ask for the sauce on the side, but to my surprise they didn't drown it sauce which made it that much better. The turkey was moist and the eggs were perfect! This is once again an awesome spin on one of my favorite breakfast foods. 

The restaurant itself is a bit like an old school diner in Old Vegas. Kind of run-down old time diner. Love it! The waitress was cracking me up because she definitely seemed clueless but she kept my coffee cup full.

This 1-star experience is based on my recent visit today at 8am.
If you want good service and hot food, DO NOT go before 11am!
NEVER ASK FOR SERVICE/HELP FROM the manager "Rose".

1. Ordered the Vegas Special to split with my friend since I don't eat a whole lot in one sitting and the pancakes are the size of your face. The waitress was so-so in her customer service skills but not the underlying reason for my review.
2. The pancakes (which are the main reason why we always go to Du-par's) came out in no less than 2 minutes after ordering which tells me they were not freshly made because it takes longer than 2 minutes to make pancakes, scrambled eggs, and bacon.  I was timing this as I was in the middle of texting a friend who happens to be a chef about how amazing Du-par's pancakes are.
3. The pancakes were lukewarm, NOT what I am used to, and too brown to have been something that was prepared fresh in two minutes.  The bacon was crispy, and the scrambled eggs were slightly runny but acceptable.
4. After tasting the pancakes which were not as fluffy as we are normally used to, I decided that they were unacceptable especially for the price of 2 pancakes.
5. I went to the managers who were huddled in a talking session behind the dining counter to ask politely yet directly if I could get hot pancakes.  Simple request, hot, not lukewarm.  Being of an educated mind I assume most people understand the difference.  If they were hot that means they would have been fresh.  Keep in mind, I KNOW how to make pancakes and when they come hot off the grill guess what... they are hot and fluffy, NOT lukewarm and dark like they had been sitting under a heat lamp.  I would have asked our server to change out our food but we were already dissatisfied with her lack of service with a smile. 
6. The manager ROSE brought out our food within 2 minutes, again, with an attitude. I must add I train in customer service and have owned a business so I understand that the customer in most given situations is always right and no manager should be rude with a customer, ever! Here is how the conversation went down:
   -Manager Rose, "I touched your pancakes and they were still warm." = strike 1, I asked for HOT not warm, and why are you bringing this up instead of simply saying, "Here I hope these will work for you."
   -My response,"I understand but when we come here, which is ALWAYS, the pancakes are hot."
   -Manager Rose responded with horrible micro-expressions and a defensive posture,"I have been a manager here for 5 years, I know how they are made."
 Rose then walks off in disgust = strike 2.  Congratulations Rose, I have no idea how you kept your job in a hospitality town with an attitude like that.  Considering that this wasn't my first eating rodeo at Du-par's I am rather familiar with how I normally get my pancakes and never have they been this poor as if we got the dregs of the morning rush pre-made pancakes that were sitting under heat lamps.  

After such horrible service from a person who should be teaching her staff on service, which would explain the lack of smiling we got from our server, we proceeded to eat our new plate of pancakes.  Again, lukewarm heat lamp pancakes. 
The server came out with a smile, finally a smile, after I had mentioned I was going to leave a bad Yelp review.  She tried to back up her manager by saying that if I put cold butter on a pancake it will make it cold. Honestly I am sure they assumed I was a moron and failed to touch my pancake I was already questioning the first time around.  I showed her that I sit my hot coffee on my cold gold wrapped butter to warm it up so I can easily spread it on my pancake.  Again, not my first eating experience ever in the history of my existence.
Another manager saw that I was obviously upset and came over to see if she could assist.  This lady had no idea what to do except give my a baffled face, Rose was apparently the General Manager.
My friend had decided that enough was enough and left her meal,"I'll meet you out in the car."  I exited as well. I have never left a half eaten meal, or a half drank cup of coffee.  We were given no apology, or even a discount for eating what would have been summed up as tripe if I wasn't a previous Du-par's fan.

My friend and I went directly home to call Du-par's see if we could get some sort of explanation as to why we received incredibly horrible service with no regards to an old Vegas saying "the customer is always right", especially if the customer doesn't have the I.Q. of a carrot and grew up in Las Vegas along with the rest of her friends and family who date back to the original Las Vegas High School when it existed on an old dusty road.  We called 3 times yet for some odd reason they were out, OR too busy to talk to us.  We literally live 5 minutes away, so to be magically out or busy in the time it took us to get home and place a call seems rather suspicious.

Regardless, I will eat at Du-par's again, only in the eveni
Consistently tasty.  Tried the pancakes this time.  They were good, but I like mine a little crispier. French dip and shrimp cocktail were delicious.

Meh. Pancakes have about a pound of butter on them, too dense and wet. Our 21 yo son didn't eat them. Our service was not great, to say the least, but the couple who sat behind us were treated markedly better than us. Not impressed with manager either. Don't go with more than 6 people because they won't accommodate 8 and get crabby if you squeeze into a booth. Kid's 21st bday and we wanted to be together. Bummer because I wanted to love this place. The adult Mac and cheese was really good.

Had dinner here last night. Started with the prawn cocktail and had the hearty beef stew. The prawn cocktail is huge! You can probably share it between two people. I loved the stew, it was exactly what I needed after a long flight. Our server Hector was sweet and very helpful, thanks!

Perhaps my problem is that no one at our table ordered the pancakes. Those seem to  be the big thing that most people are 5-starring.

I gotta tell you, though, the omelete fillings are a awfully skimpy. They say there is pepperjack cheese in the Denver omelete. I didn't see a shred of cheese in mine. Perhaps I should've sent it out for forensic analysis. And if these were three-egg omeletes, they must've been pigeon eggs.

I've enjoyed much, much bigger omeletes with way more generous ingredients, for significantly less than Du-Par's $12.50.  All four of our hash brown orders were burnt.

There's nothing "wrong" with Du-Par's. But there's just not a whole lot *right* with it, either.

This is a cute little place with awesome breakfast, great coffee and amazing homemade jelly. Just what we needed after being up so late the night before. They are at one end of Fremont Street downtown. (That was another fun thing to experience, especially late night, lol.)

I had the avocado turkey Eggs Benedict which was delicious. My sister started moaning after having a bite of her pancakes, so the table ordered a short stack to share... then we were all moaning, lol. I am not a pancake person but if all pancakes tasted like these, I surely would be. OMG! We discovered later that they call them legendary and Esquire Magazine calls them the Best Pancakes in the U.S.

So... I'm staying at golden gate hotel and i intend on having most of our meals here...
 i don't like pancakes and my daughter hates breakfast food but since everyone seems to be raving about the pancakes we had to find out what all the buzz is about... and our verdict.... OMG they are the best pancakes we both had ever had... there was a slight crunch to the edges and so fluffy in the middle... melt in your mouth... and we also tried the eggs benedict... we enjoyed those as well... i really like the way the eggs weren't so runny but i wish they would give a bigger serving of hashbrowns...
Then a late night snack i guess... what they're known for... the shrimp cocktail... it was good but i honestly haven't had one that i didn't like... BUT the price was great 3.99 and it was good enough for me and my daughter...

Ok day 2 at dupars... blueberry muffin.. they warm it up. .. moist and it's alright... the blueberries are so big it kinda freaks me out cuz i think they're some kinda bug.. hehehe but they're not. .. and i had the fresh oj... loved it. ..

Absolutely ghastly. Waited in line for roughly 20 minutes. Which wouldn't have been an issue if there weren't 10 open table that simply hadn't been bussed. The two ladies running the cash register and being hostesses were so disorganized and running around like chickens with their heads cut off should have been out first sign. We sat down and ordered out food, after being told about how amazing it was by multiple people. I ordered the BLT Avo with French fries. It came with entirely too much mayo, the fries weren't seasoned and I could have made it myself at home and it would have been better. Mike ordered the Corned Beef Hash with scrambled eggs. The eggs came out extremely wet. To the point were he grabbed a napkin to dab at them to soak up the excess liquid and raw eggs. The Corned Beef looked and tasted like cat food and wasn't even hot. The waitress saw him dabbing at the eggs and chuckled and asked "ohhh, are they a little too wet? I'm sorry" she was told yes and then asked (in what seemed like annoyance with us) "do you want me to send them back?". Mike said it was fine and she brought him more napkins. We waited 30 minutes for food we literally could have made at home and it would have been better. We witnessed the waitress be extremely rude and condescending to guests. Granted the guests were difficult, rude remarks back and slamming coffee on the table is not the answer with handling that. The check came to roughly $35 for our breakfast and a single cup of coffee. WAY over priced for what we received. The whole experience from start to finish was absolutely dreadful for a place we had such high hopes for. We will not be returning, EVER.

So where do I start. I went by the reviews, and decided to eat hear. First we waited 20 minutes to get seated. When we finally sat down. The waitress attended to us like we were bothering her. At least that's the expression we got. We ordered 2 burgers. One mushrooms and Swiss and the Steakhouse burgers. You would think that being the oldest restaurant they would have cooking down pat. I asked for Medium rare. I was more like Well dry. Probably was that way, since it took 40 minutes to get our food. For being Harris Ranch Beef, it sure tasted like cardboard. I'm not impressed. The pancakes looked good as they passed by. But that's just by looking. For sure my burger wasn't worth the $15 I paid for it. Since the food took so long we didn't even bother to ask for the homemade desserts. Just be ready to smell like a Diner when you get out. From my personal opinion save your money. Don't go by the star rating on this one. If you eat here, just expect that your at Denny's and your probably better off eating at Denny's.

It was way past "TIME TO EAT" and we were getting cranky.  Spotty cell service made it difficult to "check in" and access my bookmarks. I took a wild guess at the name of this place, and came up with "Du-Mar's".  Close enough; they knew where to send us. We had to poke around a bit to find it, tucked in behind the gaming machines in the casino.  We were there during what would be considered brunch/lunch time.

Three seating areas: 
1) In the front, just through the area cordoned off from the casino, near the pie cases and cash registers. It's more like a vestibule than a dining room.  Some pies were not in the cases- maybe they were cooling? There's also a video screen showing bakers making the pies.

2)Through another doorway, there's a diner counter with stools, some booths and tables. From here you can watch chefs through the service window, the wait staff pouring coffee, etc.

3)Through the next doorway, there's a third seating area with mostly tables.

We were seated quickly (only waited a minute or so while the hostess/ cashier rang someone up) and found a clean table near the counter. The server was there two seconds later with menus. A different person came by with water as soon as he left.

We ordered a full-stack and a half-stack of brioche French Toast, two servings of bacon, and a chef's salad.  About halfway through the 1/2 stack, I was pretty much full. My girlfriend, bless her heart, was going to town on her full stack, and even ordered a side of scrambled eggs.  My buddy enjoyed the salad (I swiped his 1/2 of a hard boiled egg), except for the bleu cheese, which was really STINKY and potent, but in a good way.

Prices throughout Vegas are sort of ridiculous, especially for food. FOUR strips of bacon = $5.25?  The food was good, but slightly expensive. I say that from the "Jersey Is Full Of Diners' viewpoint.

We didn't see any drunks, although more than one person was carefully nursing a hangover.  The wait staff were all polite and cooperative, with several people stopping by to see if we needed anything. The check showed up promptly, and they brought us a stack of extra napkins with no b*tching.

Forgot about the shrimp cocktail until we were too full to eat another thing. DAMMIT! We'd go here again, but probably not when it's full o'drunks.

One night over the summer I was at Freemont Street with some people I knew.  The night was filled with a few beers and some walking around.  One of the guy suggested this place in the Golden Gate casino.  I had never heard of the place.  So with our late night munchies in full effect we were seated at our table.  As I sat down I  immediately took out my trusty mobile Yelp app to investigate what the menu items looked like.  I started reading reviews and all I kept seeing was pancakes, pancakes, and more pancakes.  A bunch of of reviews that read, "get the pancakes!"  

I sat there in a bit of an slight inebriated state.  The waitress seemed a little annoyed as the rest of my party already ordered.  I stared deep into the menu and do you know what I ordered?  A cheeseburger..... (Record scratch.)  

Yes a plain 'ol cheeseburger.  Like I mentioned before I was a little intoxicated and I panicked.  The table laughed at me because I keep saying I should get the pancakes.  Our food came and one of the guys ordered these delicious pancakes.  Keep in mind these are the pancakes that Esquire magazine voted the best pancakes in the nation.  

I ate half of my cheeseburger and asked the guy who ordered the pancakes if he wanted to trade.  They give you a lot of pancakes so he had a lot let over.  So I sat there eating the pancakes he ordered, with a big smile on my face.  

I have since come here a few time with my family.  I was sober these other times.  I have to say the wait staff is great.  They are some of best.  If you are downtown or want to go enjoy some great pancakes then you have to come to Du-Pars.  Don't forget to order the pancakes!  Cheers!

Located downtown on Fremont Street, in the Golden Gate Casino.  I've been reading all of the fantastic reviews on this California restaurant legend and finally got to try it last week.  

Our party of four all ordered breakfast and, yes, they do have some good pancakes!  I don't know if they're the best ever, but pretty darn good.  Quite buttery, yum!  I don't know if the trio of homemade jellies were for the toast or the pancakes but they were pretty tasty as well (strawberry, apricot, and boysenberry).

Like any other breakfast, the eggs, breakfast meats, and potatoes (frozen shredded style) were pretty standard/average.  FYI, the orange juice IS FRESH squeezed.  My other dining companions mentioned they serve a good cup of coffee.

Our server was very nice and attentive.  She seemed like a good fit for the Du-Par's style restaurant.

The pancakes are not all they're cracked up to be, far from, actually. My one star is for the fresh orange juice. I had the saddest hash browns ever, lousy sausage, mediocre eggs and some toast I didn't even care to touch. Could have had the same meal at Denny's for half the price and with better service. On top of that, we had to wait more than half an hour for our meal which of course arrived right at the moment where we had almost decided to leave the god awful place. Unacceptable and below all standards.

First and foremost... Come early to avoid long lines. This hidden gem gets packed with a line that wraps around the entrance out to the casino floor. The reason for this long line is the menu. My infamous top three choices are the following.

Pancakes, on the one hand, have a buttermilk flavor that leave your mouth wanting more. On the other hand, homemade jelly in raspberry, strawberry and peach made with just the right amount of sugar is a jackpot. I apply it to my toast and I kid you not, it taste like a pastry. Lastly, the notorious shrimp cocktails makes Dupar a hit! Just beware they are packaged in a small cup and you will not be content with just one serving. Give it a try and as always Happy Eating!
Came in for the famous 2.99 shrimp cocktail. Had a piece of pie. Service was good, food was ok. Nothing Special

Stopped here for a late breakfast!  We heard about there legendary pancakes which lives up to the hype.  Everything was great including the service.  Our waitress was excellent and even gave us a voucher for money off our bill.  This place is a must visit if you are ever in downtown Vegas.

We're so happy to have found Du-Par's! A quick walk from the Golden Nugget where we were staying this past EDC weekend. We ate here twice, once one of our waitresses was amazing, the next time the other one not so great. I ordered their tuna melt both times! Probably one of the best I've ever had. Super fresh tuna and not super greasy. They also had really fresh french fries, and their ranch dressing tasted great.

They also had a fun history place mat that you could look at while you were waiting.

I'm sorry we didn't get a chance to try their pies or pastries!
Not the same as I remember it from other trips, but the short stack is really good, and plenty. The service is good, but the food is a little pricey.

This place is a definite meh. 

I've heard nothing but amazing things about the pancakes here at Du-Par's, but I was left heavily underwhelmed after eating the Vegas Stack. I arrived here around noon and right off the bat saw signs for a famous shrimp cockatil, why not, it's only $3.99. This was pretty much a serving of pre frozen then thawed shrimp with bottled cocktail sauce. There was a lot it and yet it wasn't that tasty. 

On to the flapjacks, they were buttery, fluffy and tasty, but felt very reminiscent of IHOP pancakes. I mean you drown anything in butter and syrup and I'm sure it will taste decent. These were good, not great. My fiancÃ© and I split this and ordered our own meals. 

I went with the egg white omelette filled bacon, cheese and avocado. This was very good and a decent portion size. Fluffy eggs and crispy bacon, covered in cheese? Sign me up! 

They didn't offer iced coffee which I still can't believe is happening in 2016, and I almost had to beg for water. Our waitress was basically a cartoon, classic waitress outfit, a little older, sassy and didn't GAF about anything. Our total bill was over fifty dollars with tip! Pretty pricy for mediocre pancakes and subpar shrimp cocktail. 

All hail the omelette for saving this breakfast/ lunch meal.
Can't get enough of this place. Every time we go here it is great. The fresh jams are really the best part. I always put the strawberry jam on my pancakes. Prices are pretty reasonable for breakfast.

I had heard that this is the place to have the best shrimp cocktail in Vegas. I wanted to try one as well as have lunch. The hostess who seated us was great. She was friendly and helpful and admitted she had only been on the job four days but that didn't matter her job was well done. The waitress who we ordered from is another story. She was not helpful and sort of bordered on semi-rude. Getting an ice tea refill was a major project. As for the shrimp cocktail, it was good. The rest of the lunch was just so-so. I would not go back to this place for another meal. There are too many better places in Vegas to eat.

Eventhough it started in the LA area, reminds me of a SFO restaurant. Worth the wait.
No matter what time of day, ya gotta have a shrimp cocktail. $2.99. Had one with breakfast for New Years.

This place is as advertised. The pancakes are amazing and it's a great diner experience. The pies are homemade, the pancakes are infamously great and service is very good. Our group are here multiple times and it was consistently very good. Go!
Had to get some of Du-Pars buttermilk flapjack goodness!.....still the best pancakes I have ever had.....never disappoints.....excellent service....five star breakfast.

The best breakfast! Only four stars because most times service is not that great. We have tried the pancakes, ham and eggs, French toast, muffins and of course the shrimp cocktail. All has been so delicious. The pancakes are so good you don't need syrup. The French toast is amazing! The muffins are so fresh. The jelly served with the toast is homemade. What makes the shrimp cocktail so good is the cocktail sauce which has a kick to it. I can't say enough great things about the food. Definitely worth a try!

Awesome great place! Love the vintage decor and feel of the place. The pancakes are actually very good, along with all of the other food. We also had to order the world famous shrimp cocktail and were glad we did. The shrimp were very fresh and the cocktail sauce was spicy and horseradishy!

if you can get over the fact that you have to walk through a small, dirty, ghetto ass casino to get to Du-par's, i'd recommend it! haha we went in the afternoon and the card dealers were wearing white button up shirts and black slacks but apparently at night they turn into ugly strippers. huh?? 

we've been to the Du-par's in LA at the Grove and decided to go to this one in Vegas since we were staying in downtown. they are open 24 hours, like the other locations and the pancakes are still really good. 

we split a short stack and the bacon, avocado and cheese omelet. the pancakes were crispy and so buttery. we ordered the omelet with egg whites only, and im not sure if that was the reason but it was a little rubbery. the omelet came with a side of hash browns which were cooked perfectly, with a real good crisp on it. the omelet also came with a side of toast or muffin. i got the banana nut muffin which looked good, but was pretty bland like they forgot to add any sugar. the only sweet part of it was the few slices on banana in it. 

if i was staying in downtown Vegas again, i'd go to Du-par's. just dont go expecting it to be a 5 star place, or any other place that would be on the strip. this is downtown!
Great breakfast!!  Pancakes were excellent!! Nice atmosphere!!
Place has a good vibe. Had the patty melt for breakfast and it was cooked perfectly medium. I appreciated it.

Go early ~8:30am otherwise long line. 
Easiest to split the short stack w/others and then get own plate. 

Eggs Benedict is ok but wouldn't order again.
Banana muffin was fresh but ok; more like a cornbread. Skip next time.

Would go back just for the pancakes!

Had a great breakfast!!! Located inside the Golden Gate hotel which is recently renovated with a fun 1930's vibe.

Started with a fantastic cinnamon roll!! (which I think they sold out of right after us, all bakery items made fresh every morning, but when they r gone they're gone)

Had fun reading their place mats which had fun facts about the hotel and Fremont while waiting for our food. "1933 prohibition ends, Fremont stunned to discover whiskey had been illegal" 

For my breakfast I went with eggs Benedict which was on point!  Perfect hollandaise sauce!

Overall menu is very basic but very good. Wait staff helpful and fun. Cant wait to be back for pie looked awesome.

Three hostesses, five parties in line, complete disorganization and chaos and they weren't even that busy.  These inept ladies could not keep track of menus, tables, or who was next (kinda the whole reason for a hostess).  They were rude and not in that endearing 'sassy' way.   They humiliated a poor woman for having her baby stroller on 'wrong' side of the rope.  They constantly checked and rechecked information with each other and with the poor hungry people in line and still sat parties in a way that made no sense once you got an eyeball on how the dining area was set up.  I think people were too afraid to protest for fear of being put to the back of the line.  Kind of ruins the 'best-pancakes-in-America' experience if you ask me.

This place was pretty good.  I had heard about their pancakes from a co-worker and saw all the reviews here.  

First off, I wouldn't say that these were the best pancakes I ever had.  They were really satisfying.  But I would never recommend someone go out of their way just to try the pancakes.  However, if you like pancakes or are looking for a nice little diner, this is a great place to go.

Pancakes are huge, but deceptively light and fluffy.  At even IHOP, I will eat one of their plates of pancakes and be really full and sick after.  I did not feel that way here which is a big plus.  Perfectly filling.  I like my pancakes really buttery, so I asked for more.  They bring the little packets as well as melted butter.  

We also ordered a bacon and eggs meal to split.  The bacon and eggs were good enough.  The hash browns were meh.  I would also avoid the pork sausage, which someone else in our group had.  However, this meal also came with bread and jelly.  They brought fresh strawberry and fresh blackberry jelly.  Even with the pancakes, I scarfed down the toast because the jellies were so good.  

They also have fresh squeezed OJ.  

Service was good here.

We will definitely be back to try dinner and some pie!

Good pancakes. They know how to make eggs right, which for some reason is becoming a dying art. Not going to be one of those famous "Vegas deals" on good food for low price. You pay for this one. You want the eggs with the pancakes, 2 different meals, not a combo like most places. 

It is an old school diner, so it's fairly small. Waitstaff is pretty busy constantly,  so not much chitchat out of them. Take that as you will. Hold them up making small talk, and you might make some people upset that are wanting their food.

Yummy food. Coffee was a little weak.
I ordered eggs with hash browns, comes with toast or fresh baked muffin. I opted for the muffin... blueberry goodness. Mom and Dad split a Denver omelet with hash browns and toast served with 2 kinds of homemade jam. Mom loved the strawberry jam.
 We split a stack of pancakes... with yelpers raving about the pancakes, we couldn't pass them up. 
The pancakes are the best in the city... better than the pancake house .. and wayyy better that Ihop.
We had enough food left to feed our hungry young Amanda who was stuck at work... sorry, Manda-Boo you missed out on a yummy breakfast!
The service was friendly. It wasn't crowded. The food arrived within 10 minutes of ordering it and Lupe brought coffee by at least 4 times!
Great breakfast!!! ... fresh, but weak coffee.
Next time I'll take Torrance!
The best country fried steak ever! Will definitely try to get back here when in Vegas again..

Stopped in for lunch. This restaurant was one of the few places open at 1 pm. Ordered one hotcake as an appetizer to give it a try since it is so highly rated and goodness was it delicious. The hotcake was fluffy with butter and tasty maple syrup...amazing!! I also ordered the burger with blue cheese and horseradish sauce and it too was really good.

One must have you need to order here: shrimp cocktail for $2.99 full to the rim! I came here for lunch and I was starving. The shrimp cocktail was so refreshing and good! I gobbled it all up within 10 minutes. We came here for lunch and to be honest, I really really wanted to order 2 more orders of shrimp cocktail....but my friend was giving me the eye so I got the burger instead. It was pretty good. This is your typical american joint -- had an old time feel to it. Think midwest american diner. Would probably come here again if I were in the Fremont street area.
Pricey for basic breakfast, but it's really good basic breakfast. The pancakes are perfect and fluffy. They ladle melted butter on it. Yum. Busy spot had a bit of a wait. Was worth it.
The best pancakes I ever had love the batter and clarified butter. The pies are so tasty as well. Great late night spot.

Bay City Diner... I miss you. 

Du Pars is decent food ok but grossly overpriced for breakfast. Two friends and I had breakfast there. Simple fare... Pancakes, eggs, bacon, toast.glass of OJ or coffee.  Total tab for 3 of us over $50. Seriously.

Also have eaten dinner there and it is also overpriced. I mean come on... This is a diner for crying out loud. On Fremont Street. Not the strip. 

Bay City used to be a great deal for good food but Du Pars is a disappointment.
A hidden treasure on Fremont downtown - Golden Gate casino's 24hr cafe - breakfast available all day and highly recommended.
Classic old school dinner. Went here few times and never disappoint. Great food selection,place is open 24/7 as well. I recommend the beef liver or meat loaf. But pretty much anything u get is great.

Absolutely the worst service. I got seated at the counter and it took a good 5-6 minutes before anyone greeted me. WHen I did greeted the waitress asked me if I was ready to order, (no sorry for the wait or hi hello) I told her i've been waiting for 5 minutes to order and she doesnt respond back. After she took my order she never stopped by, she never refilled my coffee had someone else refilled my coffee. After someone else dropped my food, no one came by to ask me how my food was. All this time at the counter I sat next to a dirty plate. Place like this doesnt care about the service cause either way people come in regardless. Very very disapointed in the service. I will never go back here again.

A few years back during a trip to LA, we stopped by the original Du-Pars in the Farmers Market after it was suggested to us by family. It was our first time there and we ended up just getting pancakes since they are basically "world famous". While on their own they are really really good pancakes, I could never justify going back to the LA location since there are just way too many excellent breakfast joints minutes away. So when the one in Vegas opened, I waited a while to give them a try to see if they lived up to the hype. We've now been there twice, and while the pancakes are still excellent, they just don't seem to do much else well in my eyes.

Located inside the Golden Gate Casino, this Du-Par's is pretty small and tucked back into a corner. There's a small bar and seating that sits maybe 40 or so people. Both times we've been here, we've had a decent size group of 6 or more and have had to wait to be seated. This last visit brought a group of 8, and while we didn't have to wait too long, it drives me nuts seeing restaurants leave open tables throughout the place without seating people. I can only guess this falls back on their servers and other employees. More than one time during our most recent visit, the cashier basically got into arguments with customers. And for whatever reason, our original server just up and left after taking our orders so we had to switch servers in between ordering and getting our food. It was strange, but we lucked out since our second waiter was a huge improvement.

Much like the original LA location, this one is pumping out some of the better pancakes you'll find, especially in Vegas. They're soft, but still have a little chew to them and I imagine that using real butter plays a huge part in making these what they are. You don't get the greasy feeling or overly doughy center that is common with a lot of breakfast joints. While I do like them and it's clear that they use higher quality ingredients, I'm a huge fan of unique and out of the box pancakes, so these just aren't the be all end all for me. 

Now that I've been here a couple times, I've had the opportunity to try other items and that's an area where I feel they fall short. I recently tried their corned beef hash. The $14 price-tag is to be expected in a casino, but with fairly small portions it's definitely not the best bang for your buck. Not being a huge fan of hash browns in general, I didn't care for these much, but they aren't terrible. The hash was decent, but even after ordering it extra crispy, it was still a little on the mushy side for me. I also found it strange that they don't seem to really season anything on the plate. Nothing a little bit of salt and pepper can't help. I will say I do like their fresh jams served with the toast though. 

I have to agree with a lot of other reviewers who suggest that Du-Par's maintains such a high average for their pancakes alone. They obviously can not correct their service issues, and other stuff on the menu doesn't seem to be anything special. Being that we're locals, we'll probably be back at some point, but even the pancakes aren't worth going out of the way for.
The pancakes were as good as advertised! My father had the french toast and loved it as well. Freshly squeezed orange juice and crispy bacon were also good.

After passing the locations at Farmer's Market in LA and near the arena in San Diego many times, I finally stopped into our local location at the Golden Gate. 

We ate pie, and it was good. 

I had the pecan, served warm with a generous dollop of whipped cream. 

Simple, classic with great service. Interested in coming back to try one of their breakfasts.
My sister went at dupars las year she loved it. This place's very close to the Freemont street. The Prime rib's very tender and juicy.

Heard so many great reviews about their shrimp cocktail so we've decided to go there and try it out. It's not bad since it's only $3.99. The shrimps are mediocre but their sauce made it a delish shrimp cocktail. Also tried their chicken pot pie, it was tasty and I liked it!

I enjoyed Du-par's. I have been here several times now. Some times, I go to the section inside of the Golden Gate Casino past the blackjack tables and the bar for the 

$1.99 Shrimp Cocktail: It's the best flash-frozen shrimp deal in town. I've tried Lanai's and haven't mentioned theirs. Need I say more? 

I have also tried the side of Du-par's with the sit-down restaurant. The service was really good and cussing is not tolerated there, as some gentlemen cussing were asked to stop and they left, but the manager didn't care. All the guests clapped their hands for the manager. 

When my love and I ordered, we got their 

Buttermilk Pancakes: as the recipe has been the same since dinosaurs roamed the flat earth. The pancakes are really moist, fluffy and buttery. 

The Chicken Fried Steak: was really delicious as well. This is a good place to go to when you're hungry for breakfast at any time in the day, but want something more home-made than Denny's. 

I will be back.

I was staying at the Fremont and looking for a place to get a quick bite to eat and Du Par's drew my attention. It's located in the Golden Gate hotel and was easy enough to find. 

However, I was not very impressed with the food and prices. I ordered the chicken pot pie and it just wasn't that good - didn't have a flaky crust, and the filling was just kind of average - plus, it cost around $15? Not worth it. I know a lot of people get the pancakes here, as well as the glass of shrimp cocktail, but I don't think I'd recommend their regular diner food. 

Now on the other hand, their pie really is worth it. I got a slice of green apple pie and that was tasty! Sweet crust, yummy crunchy apples. I love apple pie. I'd recommend just coming here for some dessert and getting dinner elsewhere. So probably 2 stars for their regular food, and 4 for their pies = 3 overall.

There's been so much hype about Dupars and it's pies and pancakes and as long as I've been living in downtown Fremont, I never really did go and try it out until now.

I went with a few of my coworkers and we decided to come here, have breakfast whilst also having a meeting.

The menu had breakfast, lunch and dinner offerings and chose to combine dinner and breakfast, it's my Hawaiian stomach!

The waitresses and the staff really are a well oiled machine. They're fast and efficient and pleasant as well.

I even loved the honesty of our particular waitress when one of my coworkers order sausage patties and our waitress immediately let her know that they were not good.

Oh snap!

She did let us know that the park links were good.

The order came out correctly and in a timely fashion while we continued our business meeting.

Now, side note;:I ordered the 8pz prime rib with a a pair of sunny side up eggs and a side of fries. Not your typical breakfast but I'm a big kid and can order and eat what I want!

It was amazing!

I even ordered a slice of Bartley Pear Pie to take with me back to the office!

From beginning to end, I was not disappointed in the food or the experience and I know my coworkers felt the same way!

Enjoy your meal!

:)

We loved the Bay City Diner that was here for years.  The breakfast here is good.  Service is usually pretty good, but this time I had some young men who seemed like they really didn't want me there.  The hostess tried everything to sit me a the bar and when I asked for another alternative they sat me waaay in the back all by myself.  This was dinner time.  I had a loooong drive home and was hoping for a shrimp cocktail and salad before an early bedtime so I could drive home overnight.  The waiters and help kept calling me "boss" and "bossman" and never even got me a second glass of water.  I asked if I could get a beer and they went out of their way not to get me one.  I never did get one this time.  

I heard my waiter offer pie and dessert to another table, but never even came back to me, just tossed the receipt (which you pay at the counter) and never came back.  I would have ordered dessert if he even just came back.  Most of my service on this trip came from the busboy or whoever this guy was.  Ate here for dinner at the beginning of my stay and it wasn't this bad..  Have had breakfast here on numerous occasions and it's always been good.

I can still recommend this place in spite of my treatment this time.  Food it generally good although for the service and location it could be cheaper.  See you next time DuPar's.

This food is so amaze. 

Their pancakes are actually THE BEST pancakes I have ever had. No doubt about it. I am getting hungry now just thinking about them! The syrup is real Vermont maple syrup too. And they are huge. 

Everything else on the menu is awesome too! I love their sandwhich trio, comes with soup or salad, your choice of a sandwhich, fries, and a piece of their DELISH pie. 

All of the pies are ridiculously good. I've only tried three of them but they were all awesome. 

The service is EH... The waitresses seem mildly miserable... But I can live with that since the food is THAT GOOD!

I love Du'Par's!

I've eaten at Du-Pars twice in the past week. I love eggs. All kinds. Chicken, duck, fish etc. Du-Pars does as close to a perfectly cooked over-easy egg as any I've ever had. It was served hot and the yolk was perfectly runny and the whites were cooked thoroughly. The bacon was great. Not the thickest I've ever had but definitely better than the standard pork paper you would get at IHOP or Denny's. Not to beat a dead horse but the pancakes really are pretty fantastic. Lightly crisp on the outside and nice and fluffy on the inside. I do have an issue with a place that does such a great breakfast but serves mediocre coffee. That is the only thing that prevents me from giving 5 stars.

I didn't dine in, I did take out because I had to rush off to my greyhound. Service was awfully slow, took something like 20 minutes to make 2 eggs, hash browns and toast. 

Place was really overpriced for what your were getting. Maybe the take out experience was just bad?

Du-Par's is your typical casual diner, and they do a really good job of it.My husband and I went there for breakfast while staying at the nearby Golden Nugget.  My husband had pancakes with eggs and bacon.  I ordered an egg white veggie omelet with hash browns. When I think of a typical diner, I often think of a "greasy spoon", but this wasn't at all.  My egg white omelet was fluffy, and it was filled with a variety of veggies.  The hash browns were crispy, and my coffee and water were refilled constantly.  They brought me nonfat milk for the coffee just as I requested. 
My husband enjoyed his pancakes.  He ordered the "Vegas stack" which was supposed to be smaller than the full stack, but there were a lot.  
All in all, this is a great, simple breakfast spot.  I enjoyed the historic pictures of Vegas and nearby on the walls throughout the restaurant.

We were staying at the Golden Nugget and were surprised to find the Du-pars in the Golden Gate - down Fremont Street.

Immediately I needed the pancakes for breakfast! My NEW WIFE...decided on the PRIME RIB ....it turned out so great - that we ate here 3 times during our trip!

Thanks Du-Pars!

Always come here because I'm local and it's 24 hours. 
Never come here for the service because one will be disappointed. Service is always mediocre at best. Usually have to beg for a drink from the waitress. Last time 3 waitress' were arguing in front of me behind the counter and talking crap about a guest.
